Boys And Girls Alone is a documentary series where 20 children between the ages of 8 and 11 discover what life would be like if they lived together without any parents. The boys and girls set up home in two different camps.

Part 2

After only three days of adventure, the boys - most of who can't cook - are wet, hungry and missing their mums. Meanwhile, the girls
have gone from baking cakes to splitting into warring gangs. Looking on, their parents decided to step in to put their kids back on track.
The children are given money to feed and entertain themselves for three days. While the boys invest in essentials like wrestling belts and
Dr Who action figures, surviving on meagre rations, the girls blow their money, filling three trolleys with huge quantities of food. That is
once they've demonstrated the age old cliche about women and map reading.
Meanwhile, Ade and Charley, who elected themselves leaders of the two villages, soon learn that power comes with its downsides as
revolution brews amongst their subjects. And the parents find it hard to watch as their children continue to struggle to get along.
As the three days looking after their own finances comes to an end, it's the boys that have done better. Whilst the girls are skint and are
reduced to smoking fake cigarettes and gambling with rabbits as the chips; the boys come together as a cohesive unit and discover that
sharing is the way to go.
